# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-gorchakov
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Prince **Adam Jerzy Czartoryski** (14 January 1770 – 15 July 1861), also known as **Adam George Czartoryski**, was a Polish nobleman, statesman, diplomat and author who served as Chairman of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The son of a wealthy prince, he began his political career as a foreign minister to Emperor Alexander I of Russia after Poland was partitioned by Russia, Prussia and Austria.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He later became a leader of the Polish government in exile during and after the failed November Uprising 1830–1831 and a bitter opponent of Alexander I's successor, Nicholas I.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In exile, he advocated for the reestablishment of a sovereign Polish state, which also stimulated early Balkan and Belgian nationalism, and intensified their desire for independence.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was a dedicated patron of arts and greatly contributed to the Czartoryski Collection.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1798, he purchased one of Poland's most important national treasures – Leonardo da Vinci's *Lady with an Ermine*, which he brought as a gift for his mother, Princess Izabela Czartoryska from Italy.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adam Jerzy Czartoryski was born on 14 January 1770 in Warsaw.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was the son of Prince Adam Kazimierz Czartoryski and Countess Izabela von Flemming.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] It was rumoured that Adam was the fruit of a liaison between Izabela and Russian ambassador to Poland, Nikolai Repnin.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] However, Repnin left the country two years before Adam Czartoryski was born, but Empress Catherine II dismissed Nikolai Repnin from his post on 10 April 1769.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His half-siblings were Teresa Czartoryski (1765–1780), Maria Anna Czartoryski, Konstanty Adam Czartoryski, Gabriella Czartoryski (d.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After careful education at home by eminent specialists, mostly French, he went abroad in 1786.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At Gotha, Czartoryski heard Johann Wolfgang von Goethe read his *Iphigenia in Tauris* and made the acquaintance of the dignified Johann Gottfried Herder and the "fat little Christoph Martin Wieland".
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1789, Czartoryski visited Great Britain with his mother and was present at the trial of Warren Hastings.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On a second visit in 1793, he made many acquaintances among the British aristocracy and studied the British constitution.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In the interval between these visits, he fought for Poland during the Polish–Russian War of 1792, which preceded the Second Partition of Poland.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was one of the early recipients of the *Virtuti Militari* decoration for valour there.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was arrested on his way to Poland at Brussels by the Austrian government.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After the Third Partition of Poland, the Czartoryski estates were confiscated, and in May 1795, Adam and his younger brother Konstanty Adam were summoned to Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Later in 1795, the two brothers were commanded to enter Imperial Russian army military service.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adam became an officer in the horse guards and Konstanty in the foot guards.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Catherine the Great was so favourably impressed by the youths that she restored them part of their estates and in early 1796 made them gentlemen-in-waiting, courtiers.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was already connected with the imperial family.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His elder sister Maria Anna was married to the then-Grand Duchess Maria Feodorovna's brother, Duke Louis of Württemberg.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On the accession of Emperor Paul I, Czartoryski was appointed adjutant to Alexander, who was now *Tsarevich*, and was permitted to revisit his Polish estates for three months.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At this time, the tone of the Russian court was relatively liberal.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Political reformers, including Pyotr Volkonsky and Nikolay Novosiltsev, possessed great influence on the tsar.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was not only close with Tsarevich Alexander, but Alexander's wife, the Grand Duchess, Tsarevna Elizabeth Alexeievna as well.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Born Princess Louise of Baden, she was married to the Grand Duke Alexander at the age of fourteen, and though she and Alexander shared a friendly bond, Alexander sought romantic comfort elsewhere.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Elizabeth Alexeievna soon fell in love with Czartoryski, who reciprocated her feelings.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After Elizabeth gave birth to a baby girl on 29 May 1799, the Grand Duchess Maria Alexandrovna, the Tsar Paul I didn't hide his suspicions, with both Elizabeth and Alexander having fair hair, and the baby having dark hair.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was then sent on a diplomatic mission to the court of Charles Emmanuel IV of Sardinia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On reaching Italy, Czartoryski found that that monarch was a king without a kingdom and so the outcome of his first diplomatic mission was a pleasant tour through Italy to Naples, the acquisition of the Italian language and a careful exploration of the antiquities of Rome.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In the spring of 1801, the new emperor, Alexander I, summoned his friend back to Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski found the emperor still suffering from remorse at his father's assassination and could do nothing but talk about religion and politics to a small circle of friends.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Against all remonstrances, he replied only, "There's plenty of time".
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Emperor Alexander I appointed Czartoryski administrator of the Educational District of Vilna (Polish: Wilno, Lithuanian: Vilnius) and curator of the Vilna Academy (3 April 1803) so that he might give full play to his advanced ideas.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He greatly improved the Polish education system.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was to keep those function until 1824.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski paid most attention to foreign affairs; as the emperor's key advisor, he exercised practical control of Russian diplomacy.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His first act had been to protest energetically against Napoleon's murder of a Bourbon royal prince, the Duke of Enghien 20 March 1804, and to insist on an immediate rupture with the government of the French Revolution, which was under Napoléon Bonaparte, whom the emperor considered a regicide.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On 7 June 1804, the French minister, Gabriel Marie Joseph, Comte d'Hédouville, left Saint Petersburg, and on 11 August a note, dictated by Czartoryski to Alexander I, was sent to the Russian minister in London to urge the formation of an anti-French coalition.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] It was also Czartoryski who framed the Convention of 6 November 1804 whereby Russia agreed to put 115,000 and Austria 235,000, men in the field against Napoleon.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Finally, in April 1805, he signed an offensive-defensive alliance with George III's United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski's most striking ministerial act, however, was a memorial written in 1805, otherwise undated, which aimed at transforming the whole map of Europe.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Austria and Prussia were to divide Germany between them.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Russia was to acquire the Dardanelles, the Sea of Marmora, the Bosporus with Constantinople and Corfu.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Austria was to have Bosnia , Wallachia and Ragusa.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Montenegro, enlarged by Mostar and the Ionian Islands, was to form a separate state.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The United Kingdom and Russia together were to maintain the equilibrium of the world.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In return for their acquisitions in Germany, Austria and Prussia were to consent to the creation of an autonomous Polish state extending from Danzig (Gdańsk) to the sources of the Vistula under the protection of Russia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] That plan presented the best guarantee at the time for the independent existence of Poland.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] However, in the meantime, Austria had come to an understanding with Britain about subsidies, and war had begun.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1805 Adam Jerzy Czartoryski accompanied Alexander I to Berlin and to Olomouc, Moravia (now Czech Republic), as chief minister.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He regarded the Berlin visit as a blunder, chiefly due to his distrust of Prussia, but Alexander ignored his representations, and in February 1807 Czartoryski lost favour and was superseded by Andrei Budberg.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Though no longer a minister, Czartoryski continued still to enjoy Alexander I's confidence in private, and in 1810, the Emperor candidly admitted to Czartoryski that in 1805 he had been in error and that had not made proper use of Czartoryski's opportunities.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The same year, Czartoryski left Saint Petersburg forever, but the personal relations between him and Alexander I were never better.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] They met again as friends at Kalisz (Greater Poland) shortly before the signing of the Russo-Prussian alliance on 20 February 1813, and Czartoryski was in the emperor's suite at Paris in 1814 and rendered him material services at the Congress of Vienna.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At the Congress of Vienna, Alexander I had also been asked to agree to a divorce for the Empress Elizabeth so that she could marry Czartoryski.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was content with the title of senator-palatine and a role in the administration.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The wedding led to a duel with his rival, Ludwik Pac.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On his father's death in 1823, Czartoryski retired to his ancestral Czartoryski Palace at Puławy.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1824 he lost the charge of curator of the Wilno University, in relation with the Philomaths trial.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] However, the 29 November 1830 uprising brought him back to public life.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He became president of the provisional government established on 3 December and summoned on 18 December 1830 the *Sejm* of 1831, which chose General Chlopicki as dictator.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After Chlopicki's resignation on 18 January and the dethroning by the Sejm of Nicolas I as king of Poland on 25 January, Czartoryski was elected chief of the Polish National Government by 121 out of 138 votes on 30 January 1831.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In August 1831, the military situation was bad.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] General Ivan Paskevich was approaching Warsaw from the West and the commander-in-chief, General Jan Zygmunt Skrzynecki was dismissed on 9 August.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On 15 and 16 August, there were riots in Warsaw, and many imprisoned supposed traitors, notably two generals, were hanged.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski decided to resign from the government after he had sacrificed half of his fortune to the national cause.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was replaced by General Jan Krukowiecki as both head of the government and commander in chief.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Yet the sexagenarian statesman continued to display great energy.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On 23 August 1831, he joined Italian General Girolamo Ramorino's army corps as a volunteer and subsequently formed a confederation of the three southern provinces of Kalisz, Sandomierz and Kraków.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At the war's end, when the uprising was crushed by the Russians — Warsaw was taken on 8 September — he fled under false identity to the Cracow Republic, then in Austria, and from there could reach England.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Afterwards, he was sentenced to death, though the sentence was soon commuted to exile.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] On 25 February 1832, while in the United Kingdom, he kept advancing the Polish cause and with the help of influential friends, many of them Scottish, inspired the creation of the Literary Association of the Friends of Poland, based in London, but with branches in Glasgow, Birmingham and Hull.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] That same year, Czartoryski left England for France, taking up residence in Paris.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] As a magnate and arguably the most considerable Polish-émigré figure of the time – Czartoryski was Chairman of the Polish National Uprising Government, and leader of a political emigre party.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Thousands of Poles had emigrated to France in the Great Emigration.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adam Jerzy Czartoryski was an active leader of the mushrooming committees that were formed to maintain political momentum and salvage Polish cultural heritage in the exile community.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He was the founding chairman, in April 1832, of a Historical and Literary Society.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1838 he became the legal owner and founding president (for life) of the Polish Library in Paris, the first repository of polonica, books, and archives outside the territory of Poland, which had secured, with French public support, a building on the Ile Saint-Louis in the heart of Paris.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] In 1843 he bought the Hôtel Lambert on the Île Saint-Louis and his political faction came to be identified by his private address, simply as the *Hôtel Lambert*.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His tireless efforts on behalf of Poland continued well into his seventies: in 1842 he conceived a project to found a Polish settlement in rural Turkey.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski wanted to create a second emigration centre there, after the first one in Paris.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He sent his representative, Michał Czajkowski, to Turkey and purchased a forest area which encompasses present-day Adampol from the missionary order of Lazarists.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The settlement was named Adam-koj (Adamköy) after its founder, in Turkish, the "Village of Adam", whereas in Polish it was referred to as "Adampol".
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Polonezköy or Adampol survives to this day as a small village on the Asian side of Istanbul, about 30 kilometres from the historic city centre.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At its inception, the village was inhabited by just 12 people, while at its peak, there were no more than 220 people.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Over time, Adampol developed and became populated by emigrants from the unsuccessful 1848 Revolution, the Crimean War in 1853, and by escapees from Siberia and from captivity in Circassia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The Polish villagers engaged in agriculture, animal husbandry and forestry.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] After the November Uprising in 1830–1831 until his death, Czartoryski supported the idea of resurrecting an updated Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth on federal principles.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The visionary statesman and former friend, confidant and *de facto* foreign minister of Russia's Emperor Alexander I acted as the "uncrowned king and unacknowledged foreign minister" of a non-existent Poland.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski was disappointed when the hopes that had he held as late as the Congress of Vienna of Alexander I undertaking reforms failed to materialise.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] His subsequent thoughts were distilled in a book, completed in 1827 but published only in 1830, *Essai sur la diplomatie* (Essay on Diplomacy).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] According to the historian Marian Kamil Dziewanowski, it is indispensable to an understanding of the Prince's many activities conducted in Paris following the ill-fated Polish November 1830 Uprising.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski wanted to find a place for Poland in the Europe of the time.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] He sought to interest Western Europeans in the adversities facing his stateless nation, which he still considered to be an indispensable part of the European political structure.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adhering to the Polish motto, "for our freedom and yours", Czartoryski connected Polish efforts for independence with similar movements in other subjugated nations of Europe and in the East as far as the Caucasus.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Thanks to his private initiative and generosity, the émigrés of his subjugated nation conducted a foreign policy often on a broader scale than had the old Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Of particular interest are Czartoryski's observations, in his *Essay on Diplomacy*, regarding Russia's role in the world.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Above all, he aspired to reconstitute – with French, British and Turkish support – a Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth federated with the Czechs, Slovaks, Hungarians, Romanians and all the South Slavs of the future Yugoslavia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Poland, according to his vision, could have mediated the conflicts between Hungary and the Slavs, and between Hungary and Romania.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] At the same time, the Belgian people were also seeking independence.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Adam Jerzy Czartoryski died aged 91 at his country residence east of Paris, at Montfermeil, near Meaux, on 15 July 1861.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski's principal works, as cited in the 1911 *Encyclopædia Britannica*, are *Essai sur la diplomatie* (Marseilles, 1830); *Life of J.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Niemcewicz* (Paris, 1860); *Alexander I. et Czartoryski: correspondence ... et conversations* (1801–1823) (Paris, 1865); *Memoires et correspondence avec Alex.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] I.*, with preface by C. de Mazade, 2 vols.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] (Paris, 1887); an English translation, *Memoirs of Czartoryski, &c.*, edited by A.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Gielguch, with documents relating to his negotiations with Pitt, and conversations with Palmerston in 1832 (2 vols., London, 1888).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] The 1975–1976 academic year at the College of Europe was named in his honour.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/adam-jerzy-czartoryski] Czartoryski makes a cameo appearance in volume 3 of Leo Tolstoy's novel, *War and Peace*, at an Allied Council conference that takes place at Olomouc, Moravia on 18 November 1805, just before the Battle of Austerlitz.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] Afanasy Ordin-Nashchokin was the son of a poor official from Pskov, who saw to it that his son was taught Latin, German and mathematics.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] Ordin-Nashchokin began his public career in 1642 as one of the officials involved in determining the new Russo-Swedish frontier after the Treaty of Stolbovo.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] By that time, he had gained a reputation in Russia as having a thorough understanding of "German ways and things".
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] He was one of the first Muscovites who diligently collected foreign books; according to one source as many as sixty-nine Latin works were sent to him at one time from abroad.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] Ordin-Nashchokin attracted the attention of the young Tsar Alexis because of his resourcefulness during the Pskov rebellion of 1650, which he succeeded in bringing under control through his personal efforts.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] At the beginning of the Russo-Swedish War (1656–1658), he was appointed to a high command, in which he displayed strong capabilities.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] In 1657, Ordin-Nashchokin was appointed minister plenipotentiary to treat with the Swedes on the Narva River.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] In 1660, Ordin-Nashchokin was sent as plenipotentiary to a second congress, to convert the truce of 1658 into a permanent peace.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] He advised that the truce with Sweden should be prolonged and Charles II of England was invited to mediate a northern peace.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] Finally he laid stress upon the importance of Livonia for the development of Russian trade.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] On being overruled he retired from the negotiations that led to the Treaty of Kardis.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] Ordin-Nashchokin was the chief plenipotentiary at the abortive congress of Durovicha, which met in 1664, to end the Russo-Polish War (1654-1667).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] He negotiated the Truce of Niemieża and through his efforts Russia succeeded in concluding with Poland the advantageous Truce of Andrusovo (1667).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] On his return to Russia he was created a boyar of the first class and entrusted with the direction of the Foreign Office, with the title of Guardian of the great Tsarish Seal and Director of the great Imperial Offices.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] He was, in fact, the first Russian chancellor.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] It was Ordin-Nashchokin who first abolished the onerous system of tolls on exports and imports, and brought together Russian merchants with the aim of promoting direct commercial relations between Sweden and Russia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] He also initiated a postal system between Russia, Courland and Poland, and introduced gazettes and bills of exchange into Russia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] He is also associated with the building of the first Russian merchant-vessels on the Dvina and Volga.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] During his career, Ordin-Nashchokin had to constantly struggle with narrow routine and personal jealousy on the part of many of the boyars and clerks of the council.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] He was last employed in the negotiations for confirming the Truce of Andrusovo (September 1669 – March 1670).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] In January 1671 he attended upon the *tsar* on the occasion of his second marriage; but in February 1671 he was dismissed, and withdrew to the Krypetsky monastery near his native Pskov.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/afanasy-ordin-nashchokin] There Ordin-Nashchokin took the tonsure under the name of Antony, and occupied himself with charity until his death in 1680.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The **Alaska Purchase** was the purchase of Alaska from the Russian Empire by the United States for a sum of $7.2 million in 1867 (equivalent to $132 million in 2024).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] On May 15 of that year, the United States Senate ratified a bilateral treaty that had been signed on March 30, and American sovereignty became legally effective across the territory on October 18.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] During the first half of the 19th century, Russia had established a colonial presence in parts of North America, but few Russians ever settled in Alaska.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Alexander II of Russia, having faced a catastrophic defeat in the Crimean War, began exploring the possibility of selling the state's Alaskan possessions, which, in any future war, would be difficult to defend from the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Seward, the U.S. secretary of state at the time, entered into negotiations with Russian diplomat Eduard de Stoeckl towards the United States' acquisition of Alaska after the American Civil War.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Seward and Steckel agreed to a treaty for the sale on March 30, 1867.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Reactions to the Alaska Purchase among Americans were mostly positive, as many believed that Alaska would serve as a base to expand American trade in Asia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Some opponents labeled the purchase as "**Seward's Folly**" or "**Seward's Icebox**" as they contended that the United States had acquired useless land.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Nearly all Russian settlers left Alaska in the aftermath of the purchase; Alaska would remain sparsely populated until the Klondike Gold Rush began in 1896.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Originally organized as the Department of Alaska, the area was renamed the District of Alaska in 1884 and the Territory of Alaska in 1912, ultimately becoming the modern-day state of Alaska in 1959.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Russian America was settled by *promyshlenniki*, merchants and fur trappers who expanded through Siberia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] They arrived in Alaska in 1732, and in 1799 the Russian-American Company (RAC) received a charter to hunt for fur.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] No colony was established, but the Russian Orthodox Church sent missionaries to the natives and built churches.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] About 700 Russians enforced sovereignty in a territory over twice as large as Texas.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] In 1821, Tsar Alexander I issued an edict declaring Russia's sovereignty over the North American Pacific coast north of the 51st parallel north.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The edict also forbade foreign ships to approach within 100 Italian miles (115 miles or 185 km) of the Russian claim.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] US secretary of state John Quincy Adams strongly protested the edict, which potentially threatened both the commerce and expansionary ambitions of the United States.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Seeking favorable relations with the U.S., Alexander agreed to the Russo-American Treaty of 1824.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] In the treaty, Russia limited its claims to lands north of parallel 54°40′ north and also agreed to open Russian ports to U.S. ships.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] By the 1850s, a population of once 300,000 sea otters, who were skinned for their valuable fur, was almost extinct, and Russia needed money after being defeated by France and Britain in the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The California gold rush showed that if gold were discovered in Alaska, Americans and Canadians would overwhelm the Russian presence in what one scholar later described as "Siberia's Siberia".
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] However, the principal reason for the sale was that the hard-to-defend colony would be easily conquered by British forces based in neighboring Canada in any future conflict, and Russia did not wish to see its archrival being next door just across the Bering Sea.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Therefore, Emperor Alexander II decided to sell the territory.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The Russian government discussed the proposal in 1857 and 1858 and offered to sell the territory to the United States, hoping that its presence in the region would offset the plans of Britain.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] However, no deal was reached, as the risk of an American Civil War was a more pressing concern in Washington.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Grand Duke Konstantin, a younger brother of the Tsar, began to press for the handover of Russian America to the United States in 1857.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Konstantin's letter was shown to his brother, Tsar Alexander II, who wrote "this idea is worth considering" on the front page.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Supporters of Konstantin's proposal to immediately withdraw from North America included Admiral Yevfimy Putyatin and the Russian minister to the United States, Eduard de Stoeckl.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Gorchakov agreed with the necessity of abandoning Russian America but argued for a gradual process leading to its sale.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] He found a supporter in the naval minister and former chief manager of the Russian-American Company, Ferdinand von Wrangel.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Wrangel pressed for some proceeds to be invested in the economic development of Kamchatka and the Amur Basin.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The Emperor eventually sided with Gorchakov, deciding to postpone negotiations until the end of the RAC's patent, set to expire in 1861.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Over the winter of 1859–1860, Stoeckl held meetings with United States officials, though he had been instructed not to initiate discussions about the sale of the RAC assets.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Communicating primarily with Assistant Secretary of State John Appleton and California senator William M.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Gwin, Stoeckl reported the interest expressed by the Americans in acquiring Russian America.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] While President James Buchanan kept these hearings informal, preparations were made for further negotiations.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Stoeckl reported a conversation in which he asked "in passing" what price the U.S. government might pay for the Russian colony and Senator Gwin replied that they "might go as far as $5,000,000", a figure Gorchakov found far too low.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Stoeckl informed Appleton and Gwin of this, the latter saying that his Congressional colleagues in Oregon and California would support a larger figure.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Buchanan's increasingly unpopular presidency forced the matter to be shelved until a new presidential election.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] With the oncoming American Civil War, Stoeckl proposed a renewal of the RAC's charter.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Two of its ports were to be open to foreign traders and commercial agreements with Peru and Chile to be signed to give "a fresh jolt" to the company.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Russia continued to see an opportunity to weaken British power by causing British Columbia, including the Royal Navy base at Esquimalt, to be surrounded or annexed by American territory.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Following the Union victory in the Civil War in 1865, the Tsar instructed Stoeckl to re-enter into negotiations with William H.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] President Andrew Johnson was busy with negotiations about Reconstruction, and Seward had alienated a number of Republicans, so both men believed that the purchase would help divert attention from domestic issues.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The negotiations concluded after an all-night session with the signing of the treaty at 04:00 on March 30, 1867.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The purchase price was set at $7.2 million (equivalent to $132 million in 2024), or about 2 cents per acre ($4.74/km2).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Much of the money Russia earned from the sale was reportedly paid to two Americans, Thomas and William Winans from Baltimore, Maryland, who were under contract with the Tsar to build and maintain Russia's railway system.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The Winans were seen as "the robber of the Russian Treasury", contract costs had ballooned exponentially.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The Winans received six and a half million rubles of the Alaskan sale proceeds.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The Russian name for the Alaska Peninsula was *Alyaska* ("Аляска") or *Alyeska*, from an Aleut word, *alashka* or *alaesksu*, meaning "great land" or "mainland".
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The United States chose the name "Alaska" to refer to the area purchased from Russia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Seward told the nation that, according to Russian estimates, Alaska had about 60,000 inhabitants.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] This included about 10,500 who were under the direct government of the Russian fur company: about 8,000 indigenous people and 2,500 people of Russian or mixed Russian and indigenous descent (for example, having a Russian father and a native mother).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The remaining 50,000 or so were Inuit or Alaska Natives living outside of Russia's jurisdiction.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Seward also said that the Russians were settled at 23 trading posts, placed on accessible islands and at points along the coast.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] At smaller trading posts, typically only four or five Russians were stationed: their job was to collect furs from the natives for storage and then for shipment when the company's boats arrived to take the furs away.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] One was New Archangel (now named Sitka), established in 1804 to handle the valuable trade in the skins of sea otters; in 1867, it had 116 small log cabins and 968 residents.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Paul, in the Pribilof Islands, which had 100 homes and 283 residents, and was the center of the seal fur industry.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Seward and many other Americans expected that Asia would become an important market for U.S. products, and that Alaska would serve as a base for American trade with Asia and globally, and for the extension of American power into the Pacific.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Senator Charles Sumner, chair of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, sponsored the Senate bill authorizing the U.S. to approve the treaty to acquire the territory.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] He not only agreed about the benefit to trade, but also said he expected the territory to be valuable on its own; having studied the records of explorers, he believed it contained valuable animals and forests.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] He compared the acquisition to contemporary European colonial acquisitions, such as the French conquest of Algeria.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The United States Senate approved the treaty by a vote of 37 to 2.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Many Americans believed in 1867 that the purchase process had been corrupt, but W.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Dall in 1872 wrote that "there can be no doubt that the feelings of a majority of the citizens of the United States are in favor of it." The notion that the purchase was unpopular among Americans is, a scholar wrote 120 years later, "one of the strongest historical myths in American history.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] It persists despite conclusive evidence to the contrary, and the efforts of the best historians to dispel it", likely in part because it fits American and Alaskan writers' view of the territory as distinct and filled with self-reliant pioneers.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] A majority of newspapers either supported the purchase or were neutral.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] A review of dozens of contemporary newspapers found general support for the purchase, especially in California; most of 48 major newspapers supported the purchase.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Public opinion was not universally positive; to some the purchase was known as "Seward's folly", "Walrussia", or "Seward's icebox".
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Editorials contended that taxpayer money had been wasted on a "polar bear garden".
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Forty-five percent of supportive newspapers cited the increased potential for annexing British Columbia in their support, and *The New York Times* stated that, consistent with Seward's reason, Alaska would increase American trade with East Asia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The principal urban newspaper that opposed the purchase was the *New York Tribune*, published by Seward opponent Horace Greeley.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The ongoing controversy over Reconstruction spread to other acts, including the Alaska purchase.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Some opposed the United States obtaining its first non-contiguous territory, seeing it as a colony; others saw no need to pay for land that they expected the country to obtain through manifest destiny.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The transfer ceremony took place in Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Russian and American soldiers paraded in front of the governor's house; the Russian flag was lowered and the American flag raised amid peals of artillery.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] A description of the events was published in Finland six years later.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] After the flag transition was completed, Captain of 2nd Rank Aleksei Alekseyevich Peshchurov said, "General Rousseau, by authority from His Majesty, the Emperor of Russia, I transfer to the United States the territory of Alaska." General Lovell Rousseau accepted the territory.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] (Peshchurov had been sent to Sitka as commissioner of the Russian government in the transfer of Alaska.) A number of forts, blockhouses and timber buildings were handed over to the Americans.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The troops occupied the barracks; General Jefferson C.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Davis established his residence in the governor's house, and most of the Russian citizens went home, leaving a few traders and priests who chose to remain.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] After the transfer, a number of Russian citizens remained in Sitka, but nearly all of them very soon decided to return to Russia, which was still possible at the expense of the Russian-American Company.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Moreover, Ahllund's article is the only known description of the return voyage on the *Winged Arrow*, a ship that was specially purchased to transport the Russians back to their native country.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] "The over-crowded vessel, with crewmen who got roaring drunk at every port, must have made the voyage a memorable one." Ahllund mentions stops at the Sandwich (Hawaiian) Islands, Tahiti, Brazil, London, and finally Kronstadt, the port for St.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Petersburg, where they arrived on August 28, 1869.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] American settlers who shared Sumner's belief in the riches of Alaska rushed to the territory but found that much capital was required to exploit its resources, many of which could also be found closer to markets in the contiguous United States.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Most soon left, and by 1873, Sitka's population had declined from about 2,500 to a few hundred.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The United States acquired an area over twice as large as Texas, but it was not until the great Klondike Gold Rush in 1896 that Alaska generally came to be seen as a valuable addition to U.S. territory.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The seal fishery was one of the chief considerations that induced the United States to purchase Alaska.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] It provided considerable revenue by the lease of the privilege of taking seals, an amount that was eventually more than the price paid for Alaska.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] From 1870 to 1890, the seal fisheries yielded 100,000 skins a year.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The company to which the administration of the fisheries was entrusted by a lease from the US government paid a rental of $50,000 per annum and in addition thereto $2.62+1⁄2 per skin for the total number taken.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The skins were transported to London to be dressed and prepared for world markets.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The business grew so large that the earnings of English laborers after the acquisition of Alaska by the United States amounted by 1890 to $12,000,000.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] However, exclusive US control of this resource was eventually challenged, and the Bering Sea Controversy resulted when the United States seized over 150 sealing ships flying the British flag, based out of the coast of British Columbia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The conflict between the United States and Britain was resolved by an arbitration tribunal in 1893.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The waters of the Bering Sea were deemed to be international waters, contrary to the US contention that they were an internal sea.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The US was required to make a payment to Britain, and both nations were required to follow regulations developed to preserve the resource.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] The purchase of Alaska has been referenced as a "bargain basement deal" and as the principal positive accomplishment of the otherwise much-maligned presidency of Andrew Johnson.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Barker has argued that the US federal government has not earned a positive financial return on the purchase of Alaska.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] According to Barker, tax revenue and mineral and energy royalties to the federal government have been less than federal costs of governing Alaska plus interest on the borrowed funds used for the purchase.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Miller has taken the argument further by contending that US oil companies that developed Alaskan petroleum resources did not earn enough profits to compensate for the risks that they incurred.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alaska-purchase] Alaska Day is a holiday for all state workers.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksandr-nelidov] He studied law and Oriental languages in St.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksandr-nelidov] He was Secretary to the Russian embassies at Athens, Munich and Vienna.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksandr-nelidov] In 1872 he became Councillor to the Russian embassy in Constantinople.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksandr-nelidov] He directed the diplomatic office at the headquarters of the Russian army during the Russo-Turkish War (1877–1878).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksandr-nelidov] He was an active part in negotiations that led to the Peace treaty of San Stefano and later the Treaty of Berlin.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksandr-nelidov] Nelidov helped settle the Armenian Question and Balkan difficulties.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksandr-nelidov] He presided over the 1907 Hague Peace Conference.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksandr-nelidov] He died from apoplexy on 18 September 1910, which he contracted while passing through Munich on 8 August.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] Prince **Aleksey Borisovich Lobanov-Rostovsky** (Russian: Алексе́й Бори́сович Лоба́нов-Росто́вский; 30 December [O.S.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] 18 December] 1824 in Voronezh Governorate – 30 August [O.S.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] 18 August] 1896) was a Russian statesman, probably best remembered for having concluded the Li-Lobanov Treaty with China, the Peace of Constantinople with the Ottoman Empire, and for his publication of the *Russian Genealogical Book* (in two volumes).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] Prince Lobanov-Rostovsky was educated at Tsarskoye Selo Lyceum.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] At the age of twenty, he entered the diplomatic service and became minister at Constantinople in 1859.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] In 1863, a regrettable incident in his private life made him retire temporarily from the public service, but four years later he re-entered it and served for ten years as an assistant to the minister of the interior.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] In 1879 he was transferred to London, and in 1882 to Vienna.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] In March 1895, under Nicholas II, he was appointed minister of foreign affairs in succession to Nicholas de Giers.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] In this position he displayed much of the caution of his predecessor, but adopted a more energetic policy in European affairs generally and especially in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] At the time of his appointment the attitude of the Russian government towards the Slav nationalities had been for several years one of extreme reserve, and he had seemed as ambassador to sympathize with this attitude.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] But as soon as he became minister of foreign affairs, Russian influence in the Balkan Peninsula suddenly revived.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] All this seemed to foreshadow the creation of a Balkan confederation hostile to the Ottoman Empire, and Sultan Abdul Hamid II had reason to feel alarmed.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] Meanwhile, he considered that the integrity and independence of the Ottoman Empire must be maintained so far as these other powers were concerned.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] At the same time efforts were made to weaken the Triple Alliance, the principal instrument employed being the entente with France, which Prince Lobanov helped convert into a formal alliance between the two great powers.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] In East Asia he was not less active and became the protector of China in the same sense as he had shown himself the protector of Turkey.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] By the Yamagata-Lobanov Agreement, Japan was compelled to give up her conquests in Northeast China, so as not to interfere with the future actions of St.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] Petersburg in Manchuria and financial and political schemes for increasing czarist influence in that part of the world were vigorously supported.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] However this may be, before he had time to mature his schemes, and when he had been the director of Russian policy for only eighteen months, he died suddenly of heart disease when travelling with the emperor on August 30, 1896.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/aleksey-lobanov-rostovsky] His extensive collection of coins, particularly those minted by the Russians during their occupation of Königsberg in 1758–1761, was acquired by the Russian Museum.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] Bessmertnykh was born in Biysk in 1933, first of four children.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] He lost his father when he was 10 years old.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] Bessmertnykh joined the ministry of foreign affairs in 1957.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] From 1970 to 1983 he served as a consul at the Soviet embassy in the United States, and then headed the US department in the foreign ministry.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] In 1986, he was appointed deputy foreign minister and in 1988, he became first deputy foreign minister.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] From 1990 to 1991, he was ambassador to the United States.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] He briefly served as a Minister of Foreign Affairs of the USSR in 1991, replacing Eduard Shevardnadze, being approved by the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union on 15 January 1991.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] During the August coup of 1991, he did not lend his support to the attempt at removing Gorbachev from power, but refused to condemn the plotters.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bessmertnykh-politician] For supporting the GKChP, the government of Valentin Pavlov was dismissed and, accordingly, Bessmertnykh lost the role.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Prince **Alexander Andreyevich Bezborodko** (25 March [O.S.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] 14 March] 1747 – 6 April 1799) was a Russian politician and diplomat who served as the chancellor of the Russian Empire from 1797 to 1799.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He was the chief architect of Catherine the Great's foreign policy after the death of Nikita Panin.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Аleksander Bezborodko was born in Glukhov, in the Cossack Hetmanate of the Russian Empire (now Hlukhiv, Ukraine), on 25 March [O.S.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] 14 March] 1747, into a family of Zaporozhian Cossack noble descent.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] His father, Andrey Bezborodko, was a general scribe (chancellor), while his mother, Eudokia, was a daughter of the general judge Mikhail Zabila.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He was educated at home and at Kiev-Mogila Academy.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Upon finishing his education, he entered the public service as a clerk in the office of Peter Rumyantsev, then the governor-general of Little Russia, whom he accompanied to the Turkish War in 1768.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He was present at the engagements of Larga and Kagul, and at the storming of Silistria.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In 1774, Bezborodko was appointed colonel of the Kiev Regiment.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] On the conclusion of the Treaty of Küçük Kaynarca in 1774, the field marshal recommended him to Catherine II, and she appointed him in 1775 her petition-secretary.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He thus had the opportunity of impressing the empress with his brilliant gifts, the most remarkable of which were exquisite manners, a marvellous memory and a clear and pregnant style.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] At the same time he set to work to acquire the principal European languages, especially French, of which he became a master.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] It was at this time that he wrote his historical sketches of the Tatar wars and of Ukraine.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] His activity was prodigious, and Catherine called him her *factotum*.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In 1780, he accompanied her on her journey through Novorossiya, meeting the emperor Joseph II, who urged him to study diplomacy.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] On his return from a delicate mission to Copenhagen, he presented to the empress "a memorial on political affairs" which comprised the first plan of a partition of Turkey between Russia and Austria.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] This document was transmitted almost word for word to Vienna as the Russian proposals.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He followed this up by *Epitomised Historical Information concerning Moldavia*.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] For these two state papers he was rewarded with the posts of "plenipotentiary for all negotiations " in the foreign office and postmaster-general.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] From this time he was inseparably associated with Catherine in all important diplomatic affairs, though officially he was the subordinate of the vice-chancellor, Count Ivan Osterman.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He wrote all the most important despatches to the Russian ministers abroad, concluded and subscribed all treaties, and performed all the functions of a secretary of state.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He identified himself entirely with Catherine's political ideas, even with that of re-establishing the Greek empire under her grandson Constantine.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The empress, as usual, richly rewarded her comes with pensions and principalities.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In 1786, he was promoted to the Governing Senate, and it was through him that the empress communicated her will to that august state-decoration.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In 1787, he accompanied Catherine on her triumphal progress through South Russia in the capacity of minister of foreign affairs.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] At Kanev, he conducted the negotiations with the Polish king, Stanislaus II, and at Novaya Kaidaniya he was in the empress's carriage when she received Joseph II.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The second Turkish War (1787–1792) and the Swedish war with Gustavus III (1788–1790) heaped fresh burdens on his already heavily laden shoulders, and he suffered from the intrigues of his numerous jealous rivals, including the empress's latest favorite, A.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] All his efforts were directed towards the conclusion of the two oppressive wars by an honorable peace.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The pause of Verela with Gustavus III (14 August 1790) was on the terms dictated by him.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] On the sudden death of Potemkin, he was despatched to Jassy to prevent the peace congress there from breaking up, and succeeded, in the face of all but insuperable difficulties, in concluding a treaty exceedingly advantageous to Russia (9 January 1792).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] For this service he received the thanks of the empress, the ribbon of St.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] However, on his return from Jassy, he found his confidential post of secretary of petitions occupied by the empress's last favorite, Platon Zubov.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He complained of this "diminution of his dignity" to the empress in a private memorial in the course of 1793.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The empress reassured him by fresh honors and distinctions on the occasion of the solemn celebration of the peace of Jassy (2 September 1793), when she publicly presented him with a golden olive-branch encrusted with brilliants.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Subsequently, Catherine reconciled him with Zubov, and he resumed the conduct of foreign affairs.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He contributed more than any other man to bring about the downfall and the third partition of Poland, for which he was magnificently recompensed.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] But diplomacy by no means exhausted Bezborodko's capacity for work.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He had a large share in the internal administration also.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He reformed the post-office, improved the banking system of Russia, regulated the finances, constructed roads, and united the Uniate and Orthodox churches.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] On the death of Catherine, Emperor Paul entrusted Bezborodko with the examination of the late empress's private papers, and shortly afterwards made him a prince of the Russian Empire, with a correspondingly splendid apanage.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] On the retirement of Osterman he received the highest dignity in the Russian Empire – that of imperial chancellor.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Thanks to his influence on Paul, Bezborodko was able to convince him to restore the Chief Military Court of the Hetmanate, which had been dissolved under Catherine II.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Bezborodko was the only Russian minister who retained the favor of Paul to the last.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] During the last two years of his life, control of Russia's diplomacy was entirely in his hands.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] His programme at this period was peace with all the European powers, revolutionary France included.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He died in Saint Petersburg on 6 April 1799.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In his private life, Bezborodko spent his fortune on banquets and collections of pictures and statues.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] He provided financial support to his relatives and to authors.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] While described as seeking favor, he was also noted for being grateful and for his patriotism and abilities.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The 1777 *Short Chronicle of Little Russia* was co-authored by Bezborodko together with Vasily Ruban.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Bezborodko has also been proposed as a hypothetical author of the *History of the Ruthenians*.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The Bezborodko Palace is located at Pochtamtsky Pereulok in Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The palace was built in 1783–1795 to a design by Giacomo Quarenghi.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] There emerged a palace designed according to the principles of Russian Classicism.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] While the façade of the mansion looked fairly modest, its interiors were notable for their resplendence.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The interior decoration has partly survived till today.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The façade however has changed much since its erection.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Only a portico of four granite columns survived from the original façade.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] After the count's death his heirs sold the palace to the Post-Office Department that adapted the building to its needs.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In 1924 the building was given into the possession of the Museum of communications.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] During the siege it suffered badly from artillery bombardments and was closed for repair.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The museum partly resumed its display only in 1950.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In 1974 owing to a drastic state of the entire structure its major repair was started and the museum has returned to the building only thirty years later, in 2003.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The dacha is located at Sverdlovskaya Naberezhnaya in Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] The dacha was built in 1783–1784 to a design by Giacomo Quarenghi.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] It is a central three-storey building with round turrets in the corners, joined with arched galleries to two symmetrical side wings.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In the first half of the 19th century the side wings were linked by a chain railing held in the mouths of twenty-nine cast-iron lions.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] There used to be a large landscape park with pavilions.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] According to his will, Bezborodko donated 210,000 roubles for the establishment of a gymnasium, which was founded by his brother Illya, a veteran of the Russo-Turkish War, in Nizhyn.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Starting from 1820, the higher school, which received the prince's name, offered a 9-year course and was equal in status to Russian universities.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] In 1832 it was reorganized as a lyceum, specializing in physics and mathematics, and after 1840 in law.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] After 1875 the school became known as a historical-philological institute, and in 1922 it was reorganized as an institute for people's education.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Since 1939 the institution has been known as Nizhyn Gogol State University.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-bezborodko] Among notable professors who taught at the establishment were Nikolai Bunge and Pylyp Morachevskyi, and its alumni included Nikolai Gogol, Yevhen Hrebinka, Leonid Hlibov and several other notable figures.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Gorchakov was born at Haapsalu, Governorate of Estonia, and was educated at the Tsarskoye Selo Lyceum, where he had the poet Alexander Pushkin as a school-fellow.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] He became a good classical scholar, and learned to speak and write in French with facility and elegance.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Pushkin in one of his poems described young Gorchakov as *Fortune's favoured son*, and predicted his success.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] On leaving the lyceum Gorchakov entered the foreign office under Count Nesselrode.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] His first diplomatic work of importance was the negotiation of a marriage between the Grand Duchess Olga and the crown prince Charles of Württemberg.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] He remained at Stuttgart for some years as Russian minister and confidential adviser of the crown princess.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] He foretold the outbreak of the revolutionary spirit in Germany and Austria, and was credited with counselling the abdication of Ferdinand I of Austria in favour of Francis Joseph.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] When the German Confederation was re-established in 1850 in place of the Frankfurt Parliament, Gorchakov was appointed Russian minister to the diet.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] It was here that he first met Count Bismarck, with whom he formed a friendship which was afterwards renewed at St Petersburg.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] The Emperor Nicholas found that his ambassador at Vienna, Baron Meyendorff, was not a sympathetic instrument for carrying out his schemes in the East.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] He therefore transferred Gorchakov to Vienna, where the latter remained through the critical period of the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Gorchakov perceived that Russian designs against the Ottoman Empire, which was supported by Britain and France, were impracticable, and he counselled Russia to make no more useless sacrifices, but to accept the basis of a pacification.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] At the same time, although he attended the Paris conference of 1856, he purposely abstained from affixing his signature to the treaty of peace after that of Count Alexey Fyodorovich Orlov, Russia's chief representative.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] For the time, however, he made a virtue of necessity, and Alexander II, recognising the wisdom and courage which Gorchakov had exhibited, appointed him minister of foreign affairs in place of Count Nesselrode.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] During the January Uprising in Congress Poland, Gorchakov rebuffed the suggestions of Britain, Austria and France for assuaging the severities employed in quelling it, and he was especially acrid in his replies to Earl Russell's despatches.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] The Prussian support was assured by the Alvensleben Convention.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] In July 1863 Gorchakov was appointed Chancellor of the Russian Empire, expressly in reward for his bold diplomatic attitude towards an indignant Europe.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] The appointment was hailed with enthusiasm in Russia.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] A rapprochement now began between the courts of Russia and Prussia, and in 1863, Gorchakov smoothed the way for the occupation of Schleswig-Holstein by German troops.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] That seemed equally favourable to Austria and Prussia, but it was the latter power that gained all the substantial advantages.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] When conflict arose between Austria and Prussia in 1866, Russia remained neutral and permitted Prussia to reap the benefits arising from the conflict and establish its supremacy in Germany.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] In 1867 Russia and the United States concluded the sale of Alaska, a process which had begun as early as 1854 during the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Gorchakov was not against the sale but always advocated for careful and secret negotiations and saw the eventuality of the sale but not the immediate necessity.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] When the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–1871 broke out, Russia argued for the neutrality of Austria-Hungary.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] An attempt was made to form an anti-Prussian coalition, but it failed because of the cordial understanding between the German and the Russian chancellors.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] That was justly regarded by him as an important service to his country and one of the triumphs of his career, and he hoped to obtain further successes with the assistance of Germany.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] However, the cordial relations between the cabinets of Saint Petersburg and Berlin did not last much longer.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] In 1875, Bismarck was suspected of having designs to again attack France, and Gorchakov let him know in a way that was not meant to be offensive, but roused Bismarck's indignation, that Russia would oppose any such scheme.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] The tension thus produced between the two statesmen was increased by the political complications of 1875–1878 in Southeastern Europe, which began with the Herzegovian insurrection and culminated at the Congress of Berlin.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Gorchakov hoped to use the complications of the situation in such a way as to recover, without war, the portion of Bessarabia ceded by the Treaty of Paris, but he soon lost control of events, and the Slavophile agitation produced the Russo-Turkish War (1877-78).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] The Peace of San Stefano, drafted by Gorchakov, Aleksandr Nelidov, and Nikolay Pavlovich Ignatyev, redrew Ottoman boundaries to further Russia's economic and strategic plans.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] A key goal was control of the port city of Batumi on the eastern shore of the Black Sea, in addition to several strategic points in the Caucasus.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Most importantly, Bulgaria was greatly enlarged to serve as the dominant power in the Balkans and be under Russian control.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Britain, France, Germany and Austria-Hungary objected and radically reduced Russia's gains at the Congress of Berlin (13 June to 13 July 1878).
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Gorchakov was honored as first plenipotentiary, but he left to the second plenipotentiary, Count Pyotr Andreyevich Shuvalov, not only the task of defending Russian interests but also the responsibility and odium for the concessions which Russia had to make to Britain and Austria-Hungary.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] He had the satisfaction of seeing the lost portion of Bessarabia restored to Russia but at the cost of greater sacrifices than he anticipated.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] On the whole Russia was humiliated again.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Gorchakov considered the treaty the greatest failure of his official career.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] He continued to hold the post of foreign minister but lived chiefly abroad, with Dmitry Milyutin taking responsibility for foreign affairs.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Gorchakov resigned formally in 1882 and was succeeded by Nicholas de Giers.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] He died at Baden-Baden and was buried at the family vault in Strelna Monastery.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] Prince Gorchakov devoted himself mostly to foreign affairs but also took some part in the great internal reforms of Alexander II's reign: for example he submitted four projects of emancipation reform and also presented to analysis of the foreign experience of various reforms to Alexander II.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] As a diplomat, he displayed many brilliant qualities: adroitness in negotiation, incisiveness in argument and elegance in style.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] His statesmanship, though marred occasionally by personal vanity and love of popular applause, was far-seeing and prudent.
[src:alexander-gorchakov/alexander-gorchakov] In the latter part of his career, his main object was to raise the prestige of Russia by undoing the results of the Crimean War, and it may fairly be said that he greatly succeeded.
